<!-- HERO -->
<div class="hero">
  <div class="chapter-tag">
    <span>📚 Chapter 1</span>
  </div>
  <h1><span>Number Systems</span></h1>
  <p class="hero-sub">Master the foundation of all mathematics. Understand how natural, whole, integer, rational, irrational, and real numbers fit together — and why it matters.</p>
</div>

<!-- ═══════ SECTION 1 ═══════ -->
<section class="ch-section">
  <div class="sec-hdr">
    <div class="sec-num">01</div>
    <div class="sec-meta">
      <h2>Classification of Numbers</h2>
      <div class="sub">From counting to the continuum</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="why">
    <div class="why-label">⚡ Why does this matter?</div>
    <p>Every number you've ever used fits into a hierarchy. Understanding this structure is the key to solving equations, working with fractions, and eventually mastering calculus. <strong>The classification of numbers is the alphabet of mathematics.</strong></p>
  </div>

  <div class="analogy">
    <div class="analogy-ico">🏘️</div>
    <div>
      <h4>Think of it like nested neighbourhoods</h4>
      <p>Natural numbers live in the smallest neighbourhood. Whole numbers live in a bigger neighbourhood that contains the natural numbers. Integers contain that. Rationals contain integers. The Real line is the entire city — contains everything. You can enter any outer zone from an inner one, but not everyone in the outer zone came from the inner.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Each type, in plain English</h3>
  
  <p><strong>Natural Numbers (ℕ)</strong> — Your basic counting numbers: 1, 2, 3… The name says it all — these come "naturally" when you count objects. Zero is debated; in NCERT Class 9, ℕ = {1, 2, 3, …}.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Whole Numbers (𝕎)</strong> — Same as naturals, but we include zero. Zero represents "nothing," which is a meaningful quantity — you could have zero apples in a basket.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Integers (ℤ)</strong> — The number line extended in both directions. Negative numbers join. ℤ comes from the German <em>Zahlen</em> meaning "numbers." Integers let you express debt (−500), temperature below zero (−18°C), or underground floors (−2).</p>
  
  <p><strong>Rational Numbers (ℚ)</strong> — Any number expressible as $\frac{p}{q}$ where $p, q \in \mathbb{Z}$ and $q \neq 0$. Includes all integers (since $5 = \frac{5}{1}$), all terminating decimals ($0.25 = \frac{1}{4}$), and all repeating decimals ($0.333\ldots = \frac{1}{3}$).</p>

  <table class="ctable">
    <tr>
      <th>Number</th>
      <th>ℕ Natural</th>
      <th>𝕎 Whole</th>
      <th>ℤ Integer</th>
      <th>ℚ Rational</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>7</td>
      <td class="yes">✓</td>
      <td class="yes">✓</td>
      <td class="yes">✓</td>
      <td class="yes">✓</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>0</td>
      <td class="no">✗</td>
      <td class="yes">✓</td>
      <td class="yes">✓</td>
      <td class="yes">✓</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>−4</td>
      <td class="no">✗</td>
      <td class="no">✗</td>
      <td class="yes">✓</td>
      <td class="yes">✓</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>$\frac{3}{5}$</td>
      <td class="no">✗</td>
      <td class="no">✗</td>
      <td class="no">✗</td>
      <td class="yes">✓</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>$\sqrt{2}$</td>
      <td class="no">✗</td>
      <td class="no">✗</td>
      <td class="no">✗</td>
      <td class="no">✗ (irrational)</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <div class="tip">
    <span>💡</span>
    <p><strong>One-way door rule:</strong> Every natural IS a whole. Every whole IS an integer. Every integer IS rational. The arrow flows only outward — but not everything in the outer ring belongs to the inner ones.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══════ SECTION 2 ═══════ -->
<section class="ch-section">
  <div class="sec-hdr">
    <div class="sec-num">02</div>
    <div class="sec-meta">
      <h2>Rational Numbers</h2>
      <div class="sub">Fractions, decimals, and fitting numbers between numbers</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="why">
    <div class="why-label">⚡ Why does this matter?</div>
    <p>Prices, scores, measurements, GPS coordinates — almost every real-world number is rational. <strong>Finding rationals between any two numbers</strong> is a core exam skill tested on NCERT, Cambridge, and every board exam worldwide.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="key-rule">
    <div class="key-rule-lbl">🔑 Core Definition</div>
    <h4>A rational number is any number of the form $\dfrac{p}{q}$</h4>
    <p style="color: var(--txt2); font-size: 15px;">…where $p$ and $q$ are <em>integers</em> and $q \neq 0$. Its decimal expansion either <strong>terminates</strong> or <strong>repeats</strong> in a block forever.</p>
    <div class="formula">
      <div class="formula-lbl">Examples</div>
      $\frac{1}{4} = 0.25$ (terminates) | $\frac{1}{3} = 0.\overline{3}$ (repeats) | $\frac{3}{11} = 0.\overline{27}$ (repeats)
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>The Density Property — infinitely many rationals between any two</h3>
  
  <div class="analogy">
    <div class="analogy-ico">🎚️</div>
    <div>
      <h4>Rationals are like a fader with infinite positions</h4>
      <p>Between any two rational numbers, you can always find another one. Between 3 and 4 → try 3.5. Between 3 and 3.5 → try 3.25. You can keep going <em>forever</em>. There is no "next" rational — you can always squeeze one more in. This is called <strong>density</strong>.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══════ SECTION 3 ═══════ -->
<section class="ch-section">
  <div class="sec-hdr">
    <div class="sec-num">03</div>
    <div class="sec-meta">
      <h2>Irrational Numbers</h2>
      <div class="sub">Numbers that cannot be tamed into fractions</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="why">
    <div class="why-label">⚡ Why does this matter?</div>
    <p>Ancient Greeks believed <em>all</em> numbers were rational — until Hippasus proved $\sqrt{2}$ is not (legend says he was drowned for it). Irrational numbers appear everywhere: <strong>the diagonal of a 1×1 square is $\sqrt{2}$</strong>, the circumference ratio is $\pi$, the continuous growth base is $e$. You cannot do geometry without them.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="analogy">
    <div class="analogy-ico">🎷</div>
    <div>
      <h4>Irrationals are like a jazz solo that never repeats</h4>
      <p>A rational decimal either ends cleanly or cycles through a repeating phrase — like a chorus. An irrational decimal improvises forever — no block ever repeats, no matter how many digits you compute. $\pi$ has been calculated to <strong>100 trillion digits</strong> and not a single repeating block has appeared.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="key-rule">
    <div class="key-rule-lbl">🔑 Definition</div>
    <h4>A number is irrational if it <em>cannot</em> be written as $\dfrac{p}{q}$</h4>
    <p style="color: var(--txt2); font-size: 15px;">Its decimal expansion is <strong>non-terminating AND non-repeating</strong> — infinite digits with no cycling pattern.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="formula">
    <div class="formula-lbl">Famous Irrationals</div>
    $\sqrt{2} = 1.41421356\ldots$ | $\sqrt{3} = 1.73205080\ldots$ | $\pi = 3.14159265\ldots$
    <br>
    $e = 2.71828182\ldots$ | $\varphi = \frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2} = 1.61803398\ldots$ (golden ratio)
  </div>

  <h3>Proof: $\sqrt{2}$ is irrational</h3>
  <p>One of mathematics' most elegant arguments — <strong>proof by contradiction</strong>. We assume the opposite, then show it leads to an impossible situation.</p>

  <div class="tip">
    <span>💡</span>
    <p><strong>Quick shortcut:</strong> $\sqrt{n}$ is irrational whenever $n$ is <em>not</em> a perfect square. So $\sqrt{4}=2$ (rational), $\sqrt{9}=3$ (rational), but $\sqrt{5}, \sqrt{6}, \sqrt{7}, \sqrt{8}, \sqrt{10}$ are all irrational.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══════ SECTION 4 ═══════ -->
<section class="ch-section">
  <div class="sec-hdr">
    <div class="sec-num">04</div>
    <div class="sec-meta">
      <h2>Real Numbers & the Number Line</h2>
      <div class="sub">Every point has an address — and vice versa</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="why">
    <div class="why-label">⚡ Why does this matter?</div>
    <p>The number line is the foundation of coordinate geometry, calculus, and physics. Understanding that <strong>every real number corresponds to exactly one point</strong> on the line — and every point to exactly one number — is the bridge between algebra and geometry.</p>
  </div>

  <p>The set of <strong>Real Numbers ℝ</strong> = Rational ∪ Irrational. Together, they fill up the entire number line with <em>no gaps whatsoever</em>.</p>

  <h3>Constructing $\sqrt{2}$ on the Number Line</h3>
  <p>You cannot compute $\sqrt{2}$ exactly as a decimal, but you CAN find its <em>precise location</em> using geometry — the Pythagorean theorem becomes your ruler.</p>

  <div class="tip">
    <span>📐</span>
    <p><strong>Geometric Construction:</strong> Draw a number line. Mark O (origin) and A at 1. At A, draw a perpendicular segment AB of length 1 unit upward. By Pythagoras: $OB = \sqrt{1^2 + 1^2} = \sqrt{2}$. Open a compass to length OB. With centre O, draw an arc cutting the number line at C. Point C is at exactly $\sqrt{2} \approx 1.414\ldots$ on the number line.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══════ SECTION 5 ═══════ -->
<section class="ch-section">
  <div class="sec-hdr">
    <div class="sec-num">05</div>
    <div class="sec-meta">
      <h2>Operations with Irrationals</h2>
      <div class="sub">Simplifying surds, adding like terms, rationalizing</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="why">
    <div class="why-label">⚡ Why does this matter?</div>
    <p>In physics and engineering, answers routinely involve surds — $3\sqrt{2}$ is <em>more precise</em> than 4.242… and easier to manipulate algebraically. Rationalizing the denominator is tested in <strong>every board exam</strong> and is fundamental for simplifying fractions in calculus.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="analogy">
    <div class="analogy-ico">🍓</div>
    <div>
      <h4>Surds are like fruit — only the same kind can be combined</h4>
      <p>3 apples + 2 apples = 5 apples. But 3 apples + 2 oranges stays as 3 apples + 2 oranges. Exactly the same: $3\sqrt{2} + 2\sqrt{2} = 5\sqrt{2}$. But $3\sqrt{2} + 2\sqrt{3}$ cannot be simplified — different "fruits."</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="formula">
    <div class="formula-lbl">Essential Surd Rules</div>
    $\sqrt{a}\cdot\sqrt{b} = \sqrt{ab}$ | $\frac{\sqrt{a}}{\sqrt{b}} = \sqrt{\frac{a}{b}}$ | $(\sqrt{a})^2 = a$
    <br>
    $(a+\sqrt{b})(a-\sqrt{b}) = a^2 - b$ (key for rationalizing!)
  </div>

  <h3>Rationalizing Denominators</h3>
  <p>To remove a square root from the denominator, multiply top and bottom by the <strong>conjugate</strong> — the same expression with the opposite sign.</p>

  <div class="tip">
    <span>✖️</span>
    <p><strong>Example:</strong> To rationalize $\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}+\sqrt{2}}$, multiply by $\frac{\sqrt{5}-\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{5}-\sqrt{2}}$. The denominator becomes $(\sqrt{5})^2 - (\sqrt{2})^2 = 5 - 2 = 3$. Result: $\frac{\sqrt{5}-\sqrt{2}}{3}$</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══════ SECTION 6 ═══════ -->
<section class="ch-section">
  <div class="sec-hdr">
    <div class="sec-num">06</div>
    <div class="sec-meta">
      <h2>Laws of Exponents for Real Numbers</h2>
      <div class="sub">Including fractional and negative powers</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="why">
    <div class="why-label">⚡ Why does this matter?</div>
    <p>Exponent laws are the grammar of algebra. Every expression in science — from compound interest $(1+r)^n$ to radioactive decay $N_0 e^{-\lambda t}$ to signal strength — uses exponents. <strong>Master these 7 laws and you can simplify any power expression in seconds.</strong></p>
  </div>

  <div class="analogy">
    <div class="analogy-ico">⚙️</div>
    <div>
      <h4>Exponent laws are cheat codes built into numbers</h4>
      <p>You <em>could</em> calculate $2^5 \times 2^4 = 32 \times 16 = 512$. Or use the product law: $2^{5+4} = 2^9 = 512$. Same answer, a fraction of the work. Each law is a mathematical shortcut you'd discover anyway — they just name it for you.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="formula">
    <div class="formula-lbl">The 7 Essential Laws</div>
    <strong>1. Product Rule:</strong> $a^m \cdot a^n = a^{m+n}$ | Example: $2^3 \cdot 2^4 = 2^7 = 128$
    <br>
    <strong>2. Quotient Rule:</strong> $\frac{a^m}{a^n} = a^{m-n}$ | Example: $3^5 ÷ 3^2 = 3^3 = 27$
    <br>
    <strong>3. Power of a Power:</strong> $(a^m)^n = a^{mn}$ | Example: $(2^3)^2 = 2^6 = 64$
    <br>
    <strong>4. Zero Exponent:</strong> $a^0 = 1$ | Example: $5^0 = 1$
    <br>
    <strong>5. Negative Exponent:</strong> $a^{-n} = \frac{1}{a^n}$ | Example: $2^{-3} = \frac{1}{8}$
    <br>
    <strong>6. Fractional Exponent:</strong> $a^{1/n} = \sqrt[n]{a}$ | Example: $8^{1/3} = 2$
    <br>
    <strong>7. Product to Power:</strong> $(ab)^n = a^n b^n$ | Example: $(2 \cdot 3)^2 = 4 \cdot 9 = 36$
  </div>
</section>

<!-- SUMMARY -->
<div class="summary">
  <h3>📌 Chapter Summary</h3>
  <ul class="sum-list">
    <li><span>🔢</span>Numbers nest: $\mathbb{N} \subset \mathbb{W} \subset \mathbb{Z} \subset \mathbb{Q} \subset \mathbb{R}$</li>
    <li><span>🔀</span>Rational $= \frac{p}{q}$ with $q\neq 0$ — decimal terminates or repeats</li>
    <li><span>♾️</span>Irrational = decimal non-terminating AND non-repeating. Example: $\sqrt{2}, \pi, e$</li>
    <li><span>🏗️</span>$\mathbb{R} = \mathbb{Q} \cup$ Irrational — every point on the number line is a real number</li>
    <li><span>📐</span>Irrationals can be <em>located exactly</em> on the number line via geometric construction</li>
    <li><span>✖️</span>Rationalize denominators by multiplying by the conjugate: $(a+\sqrt{b})(a-\sqrt{b}) = a^2-b$</li>
    <li><span>⚡</span>7 exponent laws cover all operations with real-number powers</li>
  </ul>
